article.headline: Beard, Mosch lead way for Duke
article.linkText: Duke rips Wake Forest for 36th straight ACC win
article.story:
WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. -- Since losing for the only time this
season earlier this month, No. 2 Duke is suffocating opponents with
defense.

Alana Beard and Sheana Mosch scored 14 points each as the Blue
Devils beat Wake Forest 83-41 Monday night, winning its 36th
straight conference game. It was the fourth straight game the Blue
Devils have held an opponent to 49 points or fewer since a Feb. 1
loss to Connecticut.

The Blue Devils (24-1, 12-0 Atlantic Coast Conference) had 18
steals and forced 24 turnovers, setting up a meeting with No. 6
North Carolina on Thursday for first place in the league.

"Defense has been our trademark, especially since the
Connecticut game,'' Duke coach Gail Goestenkors said. "Ever since
then we've been really, really good. I was proud of our defense
before, but now we understand that to be a championship team, you
have to play great team defense.''

Tiffani Listenbee had 17 points to lead the Demon Deacons
(11-12, 2-11), who shot 35 percent. They have lost 10 of 11.

The Blue Devils were in control throughout, using a 15-0 run
late in the first half to take a 40-13 lead. Mosch scored seven
points in the run, while the Demon Deacons went 8:46 without a
point.

The Blue Devils led 40-18 at halftime despite Beard and Iciss
Tillis being in foul trouble. Duke then hit 14 of 22 shots after
the break to prevent any chance of a comeback.

"(Duke) took advantage of everything tonight,'' Wake Forest
coach Charlene Curtis said. "It was a combination of our being
nervous and their (defensive) presence. ... They're so active. You
think there's an open passing lane, but there's not an open passing
lane.''

The Blue Devils shot 52 percent for the game and outrebounded
the Demon Deacons 41-26. Duke also hit 17 of 26 free throws
compared to a 4-for-8 effort for Wake Forest.

Mosch's 14 points were a season-high, while Beard also had six
rebounds and four steals. Tillis and Vicki Krapohl each added nine
points.

"We were just all on the same page tonight,'' Beard said.
"They gave us a lot of opportunities for easy steals, and with
every game we're just gaining more pride in our defense. It feels
good to know Iciss and I aren't playing that well and you look up
and we're up by 22.''
